Church leaders in Narok county have asked world leaders to end the Ukrainian conflict after the invasion of Russian troops. Led by Bishop Nicholas Ndavi of World of Faith Church Praise Centre and Bishop John Mpurkoi of Pentecostal Assemblies of God (PAG) Narok church, they the leaders  should seek swift peaceful resolutions to end the violence. Speaking during their Sunday services, Ndavi called on all the nations to pray for Ukraine. “We are heartbroken and deeply concerned by the ongoing conflict in the Ukraine. Our prayers are with them and we are pleading with the leaders to seek resolutions and peace,” Ndavi said. He said that it is sad that the nation which has taken ages to build can only be destroyed in one day through conflict. The clergy said they are praying to God to give the leaders the necessary wisdom so that they can effectively handle the current challenges they are facing. “Violence is not the way to go when solving such a crisis but diplomacy and the love of God will end these challenges," he said. The bishop also said that if conflicts is not handled now, it would affect the economy of the world. Similar sentiments were echoed by Mpurkoi who said that Kenyans should be in the forefront to pray for this nation so that armed conflict will end quickly and the controversies will end peacefully. “Let’s continue to pray for peace. We know that enduring peace can be found through the Lord,” Mpurkoi said. The cleric said  many innocent lives have been affected while others displaced and the international community should move in with speed and assist the displaced refugees. “We need to stand united as the world against the invasion of Ukraine and in support of diplomacy and dialogue to bring this crisis to an end."  (edited by Amol Awuor)